The kubernetes object model.

Open any kubernetes manifest. A pod, a service, a deployment, a config map, a secret, even a custom one. You will always find the same five top level keys. Memorize these now and you will never feel lost in a new manifest again.

The first is ay-pee-eye version, which names the ay-pee-eye group and version this object belongs to. Core objects like pod, service, config map, and namespace use plain v one, the implicit core group. Newer objects carry a group prefix. Deployments live under apps slash v one, jobs and cron jobs under batch slash v one, ingress and network policy under the networking group, and are-back under the are-back authorization group.

The second is kind, the object type. Pod, deployment, service, and so on. Always capitalized, always singular.

The third is metadata, the identifying information. Every object has a name, unique within its namespace and kind, an optional namespace that defaults to default, plus labels and annotations. A few fields are system assigned, like the unique id and the creation timestamp.

The fourth is spec, which is what you want. This is your contribution. You write three replicas because you want three replicas. You write a particular image because you want that image.

And the fifth is status, which is what actually is. This is the cluster's contribution. You do not write it. The controllers fill it in. The phase, the pod eye-pee, the conditions, all status fields. You read status to understand what really happened.

The relationship between spec and status is the whole game. You declare the spec, a controller observes the difference, acts to close the gap, and records reality in status. That loop, running forever, is kubernetes.
